results.notes: Three fruitbodies were found in close proximity to each other, with several unhatched stinkhorn “eggs” also present. The eggs were covered in small soft spines, giving them an overall somewhat velvety texture, a defining trait of this species. The delicate indusiums of the specimens had dried somewhat, and hung loosely by their stipes. There was a strong spermatic odour, much stronger than that of most other stinkhorn species. I usually have to bend down close to the fungus to smell the scent of most stinkhorns, but for this species, I usually smell it before I see it. Found on woodchip mulch.

Apothecia common, deeply immersed, concave, disks black, lightly to rarely heavily pruinous. Hymenium hyaline, epihymenium dark, turning brown in K. Paraphyses moniliform. results.notes:
Though all of the matieral shown/collected was found to be immature, there are a number of key characters which point convincingly toward T. chocoënsis:

(1) The long, ocassionally “annellate” (ringed) branches arising from a main rachis, (2) which bifurcate +/- two-dimensionally (as opposed to three-dimensionally/arboreally as in T. subg. Thamnomyces spp.), (3) and terminate in swolen uniperithecial heads (5), as well as (4) the presence of yellow-brown to orange-brown subcortical granules, which are said to produce “diulte hazel” and “isabelline” KOH extracable pigments (KOH test results TBD).

The purple and yellowish-orange coloration covering different amounts of the young branches in our collection is likely the precursor to these subcortical granules. This feature is not mentioned in the type description, perhaps because material of this age was not observed.

Lastly, but perhaps most relevantly, the epithet, chocoënsis, denotes the highly biodiverse Chocó region of Colombia and Ecuador. The specific type locality of X. chocoënsis is less than 50 miles from our collection site.
